@guozhangwang TopicAuthorizationException may also be thrown as well. Pushing the exception to sender thread is an option. We can probably do this to UnauthorizedTopicException and maybe RecordSizeTooLargeException as well. I actually feel it is a little hacky that we let the producer to form a RecordSizeTooLargeException which is an ApiException. Maybe we should consider replacing it with something like IllegalArgumentException.

Regarding the TimeoutException, we are actually mixing the usage of timeout exception for two different purposes. 1) the client cannot finish something in time, it may or may not be related to the broker. 2) the broker tells the clients that it cannot finish something in time.

In case 1) it does not make sense to push the exception to the sender thread because the it is purely a client side decision. In case 2) we want to let the sender thread to handle the exception. Currently case 2) is only applicable to ProduceRequest which expect the replication to be finished within a given time. 
I think we should decouple those two. 

From what I understand, what we want here is not let callback to handle all the ApiException, it is about letting the callback handle the ApiExceptions related to the ProduceRequest and related TopicMetadataRequest. I feel a few issues we have seen in producer and consumer came from our bad exception hierarchy. e.g. a retriable exception doesn't have to be an ApiException. Maybe we should consider to use an abstract exception instead of complicated hierarchy. Something like:

```
public abstract class KafkaException  {
boolean isTriable();
boolean isApiException();
boolean isMetadataException();
...
}
```

This will give us much more freedom to handle exceptions correctly.

For this particular issue, I am thinking maybe can do the following:
1. Create a RequestTimeoutException extends from RetriableException. This exception will only be passed to the callback.
2. Let TimeoutException extend from KafkaException and this exception can be thrown to the user threads.
3. Push TopicAuthorizationException to the sender thread.
4. Replace RecordSizeTooLargeException with IllegalArgumentException.

